---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import BottomDrawer from '../../components/BottomDrawer.astro';
---

<Layout title="The Future of Web Development: Beyond React - Nolan">
  <article class="blog-post">
    <header class="post-header">
      <div class="post-meta">
        <a href="/blog" class="back-link">← Back to Blog</a>
        <time class="post-date">March 15, 2024</time>
      </div>
      <h1>The Future of Web Development: Beyond React</h1>
      <p class="post-subtitle">Exploring emerging frameworks and technologies that are reshaping how we build for the web</p>
    </header>

    <div class="post-content">
      <div class="hero-image">
        <img src="https://picsum.photos/800/400?random=20" alt="Futuristic code interface" />
        <p class="image-caption">The future of web development is closer than we think</p>
      </div>

      <p class="lead">React has dominated the frontend landscape for nearly a decade, but the web is evolving. New paradigms are emerging that challenge our assumptions about how we should build interfaces, manage state, and deliver experiences to users.</p>

      <p>The shift isn't just about new syntax or better developer experience—it's about fundamentally rethinking how we approach web development. From Server Components that blur the line between frontend and backend, to compile-time optimizations that make runtime overhead nearly obsolete.</p>

      <h2>The Rise of Compile-Time Frameworks</h2>

      <p>Frameworks like Svelte and SolidJS are pioneering a new approach: doing more work at build time rather than in the browser. This isn't just an optimization—it's a philosophical shift that's changing what's possible on the web.</p>

      <div class="content-image">
        <img src="https://picsum.photos/700/300?random=21" alt="Compilation process visualization" />
        <p class="image-caption">Compile-time optimizations are revolutionizing performance</p>
      </div>

      <p>When your framework can analyze your entire application at build time, it can make optimizations that would be impossible at runtime. Dead code elimination becomes surgical. Bundle splitting becomes intelligent. The result? Applications that start faster and run smoother.</p>

      <blockquote>
        "The best runtime is no runtime at all. Every optimization we can move to compile time is a win for users."
        <cite>— Rich Harris, creator of Svelte</cite>
      </blockquote>

      <h2>Server Components: Rethinking the Boundary</h2>

      <p>React Server Components represent one of the most significant shifts in how we think about web applications. By allowing components to run on the server and stream their output to the client, we're rediscovering the benefits of server-side rendering while maintaining the interactivity of SPAs.</p>

      <p>This isn't just about performance—though the performance benefits are substantial. It's about developer experience, security, and the ability to access data sources directly without building APIs.</p>

      <div class="slider-container">
        <div class="slider">
          <div class="slide active">
            <img src="https://picsum.photos/600/300?random=22" alt="Server Components diagram 1" />
            <h3>Traditional Client-Side Rendering</h3>
            <p>All rendering happens in the browser, leading to large bundle sizes and slower initial loads.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="slide">
            <img src="https://picsum.photos/600/300?random=23" alt="Server Components diagram 2" />
            <h3>Server Components</h3>
            <p>Components render on the server, sending only the result to the client for instant display.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="slide">
            <img src="https://picsum.photos/600/300?random=24" alt="Server Components diagram 3" />
            <h3>Hybrid Approach</h3>
            <p>The best of both worlds: server rendering for static content, client rendering for interactivity.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="slider-controls">
          <button class="slider-btn active" data-slide="0">1</button>
          <button class="slider-btn" data-slide="1">2</button>
          <button class="slider-btn" data-slide="2">3</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>Edge Computing and the New CDN</h2>

      <p>The edge isn't just about static assets anymore. With platforms like Cloudflare Workers, Vercel Edge Functions, and Deno Deploy, we can run full applications at the edge, closer to our users than ever before.</p>

      <div class="content-image">
        <img src="https://picsum.photos/750/350?random=25" alt="Global edge network visualization" />
        <p class="image-caption">Edge computing brings applications closer to users worldwide</p>
      </div>

      <p>This distributed approach to web applications opens up new possibilities for performance and user experience. Imagine personalized content that's generated on-demand, just milliseconds away from your users, anywhere in the world.</p>

      <h2>WebAssembly: Beyond JavaScript</h2>

      <p>WebAssembly is quietly revolutionizing what's possible in web browsers. From bringing desktop-class applications to the web to enabling new levels of performance for CPU-intensive tasks, WASM is expanding the boundaries of web development.</p>

      <p>Languages like Rust, Go, and C++ are becoming viable options for web development, not just for their performance characteristics, but for their ability to share code between different platforms and contexts.</p>

      <div class="code-comparison">
        <div class="code-block">
          <h4>JavaScript</h4>
          <pre><code>function fibonacci(n) {
  if (n <= 1) return n;
  return fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2);
}</code></pre>
        </div>
        <div class="code-block">
          <h4>Rust (compiled to WASM)</h4>
          <pre><code>pub fn fibonacci(n: u32) -> u32 {
    match n {
        0 | 1 => n,
        _ => fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2)
    }
}</code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>The performance difference can be dramatic, especially for computational tasks. But it's not just about speed—it's about bringing the rich ecosystem of systems programming languages to the web.</p>

      <h2>The Developer Experience Revolution</h2>

      <p>Perhaps the most exciting trend is the focus on developer experience. Tools like Vite have shown us what's possible when we optimize for the developer feedback loop. Hot module replacement that actually works. Build times measured in milliseconds, not minutes.</p>

      <div class="content-image">
        <img src="https://picsum.photos/700/400?random=26" alt="Developer workflow optimization" />
        <p class="image-caption">Modern tooling is transforming the development experience</p>
      </div>

      <p>This isn't just about making developers happy—though that's important. It's about removing friction from the creative process, allowing developers to iterate faster and build better products.</p>

      <h2>What This Means for You</h2>

      <p>If you're a developer wondering how to navigate this changing landscape, my advice is simple: stay curious, but don't chase every trend. The fundamentals of good web development—performance, accessibility, user experience—remain constant even as the tools evolve.</p>

      <p>Focus on understanding the problems these new tools solve rather than the tools themselves. That way, you'll be prepared to evaluate and adopt new technologies as they emerge.</p>

      <div class="final-image">
        <img src="https://picsum.photos/800/300?random=27" alt="Future technology concept" />
        <p class="image-caption">The future is full of possibilities for those ready to embrace change</p>
      </div>

      <p>The future of web development is bright, diverse, and full of possibilities. Whether you're building with React, exploring Svelte, or experimenting with WebAssembly, the key is to remain focused on what matters most: creating great experiences for the people who use what we build.</p>

      <div class="post-footer">
        <div class="tags">
          <span class="tag">Web Development</span>
          <span class="tag">React</span>
          <span class="tag">Svelte</span>
          <span class="tag">WebAssembly</span>
          <span class="tag">Performance</span>
        </div>
        
        <div class="post-nav">
          <a href="/blog" class="nav-link">← Back to Blog</a>
          <a href="/blog/ai-creative-coding" class="nav-link">Next Post →</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
  
  <BottomDrawer />
</Layout>

<style>
  .blog-post {
    min-height: 100vh;
    background: white;
    max-width: 800px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 4rem);
  }

  .post-header {
    margin-bottom: clamp(3rem, 6vw, 4rem);
  }

  .post-meta {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: center;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
    padding-bottom: 1rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
  }

  .back-link {
    color: #666;
    text-decoration: none;
    font-weight: 500;
    transition: color 0.3s ease;
  }

  .back-link:hover {
    color: black;
  }

  .post-date {
    color: #888;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }

  .post-header h1 {
    font-size: clamp(2.5rem, 6vw, 4rem);
    font-weight: 800;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    color: black;
    line-height: 1.2;
    text-shadow: 
      -0.08em 0 #ff3333,
      0.08em 0 #33ccff,
      -0.12em 0 rgba(255, 51, 51, 0.8),
      0.12em 0 rgba(51, 204, 255, 0.8);
  }

  .post-subtitle {
    font-size: clamp(1.1rem, 2.5vw, 1.4rem);
    color: #666;
    line-height: 1.6;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .post-content {
    line-height: 1.8;
    font-size: clamp(1rem, 2vw, 1.1rem);
  }

  .hero-image,
  .content-image,
  .final-image {
    margin: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 3rem) 0;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .hero-image img,
  .content-image img,
  .final-image img {
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    border-radius: 12px;
    box-shadow: 0 8px 25px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
  }

  .image-caption {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: #666;
    font-style: italic;
    margin-top: 1rem;
  }

  .lead {
    font-size: clamp(1.2rem, 2.5vw, 1.4rem);
    color: #333;
    font-weight: 400;
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }

  .post-content p {
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
    color: #444;
  }

  .post-content h2 {
    font-size: clamp(1.8rem, 4vw, 2.2rem);
    font-weight: 700;
    margin: clamp(3rem, 6vw, 4rem) 0 1.5rem 0;
    color: black;
  }

  blockquote {
    margin: 2rem 0;
    padding: 1.5rem 2rem;
    border-left: 4px solid #33ccff;
    background: rgba(51, 204, 255, 0.05);
    font-style: italic;
    border-radius: 0 8px 8px 0;
  }

  blockquote cite {
    display: block;
    margin-top: 1rem;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: #666;
    font-style: normal;
  }

  .slider-container {
    margin: 3rem 0;
    border-radius: 12px;
    overflow: hidden;
    box-shadow: 0 8px 25px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
  }

  .slider {
    position: relative;
    height: 400px;
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .slide {
    position: absolute;
    top: 0;
    left: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    opacity: 0;
    transition: opacity 0.5s ease;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    background: white;
  }

  .slide.active {
    opacity: 1;
  }

  .slide img {
    width: 100%;
    height: 60%;
    object-fit: cover;
  }

  .slide h3 {
    padding: 1rem 2rem 0.5rem;
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 1.3rem;
    color: black;
  }

  .slide p {
    padding: 0 2rem 1rem;
    margin: 0;
    color: #666;
    font-size: 1rem;
  }

  .slider-controls {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    gap: 0.5rem;
    padding: 1rem;
    background: white;
  }

  .slider-btn {
    width: 40px;
    height: 40px;
    border: 2px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
    background: transparent;
    border-radius: 50%;
    cursor: pointer;
    transition: all 0.3s ease;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .slider-btn:hover,
  .slider-btn.active {
    border-color: #33ccff;
    background: #33ccff;
    color: white;
  }

  .code-comparison {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 1rem;
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }

  .code-block {
    background: #f8f9fa;
    border-radius: 8px;
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .code-block h4 {
    background: #e9ecef;
    padding: 0.8rem 1rem;
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: #495057;
  }

  .code-block pre {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 1rem;
    overflow-x: auto;
  }

  .code-block code {
    font-family: 'Monaco', 'Menlo', monospace;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    line-height: 1.4;
    color: #333;
  }

  .post-footer {
    margin-top: 4rem;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
  }

  .tags {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }

  .tag {
    padding: 0.3rem 0.8rem;
    background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);
    border-radius: 20px;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: #666;
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  .post-nav {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: center;
  }

  .nav-link {
    color: #666;
    text-decoration: none;
    font-weight: 500;
    transition: color 0.3s ease;
  }

  .nav-link:hover {
    color: black;
  }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .code-comparison {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .post-meta {
      flex-direction: column;
      align-items: flex-start;
      gap: 0.5rem;
    }

    .post-nav {
      flex-direction: column;
      gap: 1rem;
      text-align: center;
    }

    .slider {
      height: 350px;
    }
  }

  @media (max-width: 480px) {
    .blog-post {
      padding: 2rem 1rem;
    }
  }
</style>

<script>
  document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
    const slides = document.querySelectorAll('.slide');
    const buttons = document.querySelectorAll('.slider-btn');
    let currentSlide = 0;

    function showSlide(index) {
      slides.forEach((slide, i) => {
        slide.classList.toggle('active', i === index);
      });
      buttons.forEach((btn, i) => {
        btn.classList.toggle('active', i === index);
      });
    }

    buttons.forEach((btn, index) => {
      btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
        currentSlide = index;
        showSlide(currentSlide);
      });
    });

    // Auto-advance slides every 5 seconds
    setInterval(() => {
      currentSlide = (currentSlide + 1) % slides.length;
      showSlide(currentSlide);
    }, 5000);
  });
</script>